result.execSummary:
The defendant Tracy J Cornell was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly conduct. This is not a criminal offense and results only in a money penalty for this offense.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Adjourned initial appearance on April 6, 2022 at 10:15 am.

09:47 AM Defendant Tracy J Cornell in court.  Alexander Paul Seifert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Tracy J Cornell appeared by video means. Court has reviewed the defendant's request for court appointed counsel, could not appoint one off the paperwork as it was incomplete, asks what he prefers to do, waive right to attorney, contact SPD, hire his own or fill out new court appointed paperwork. Cornell states he does not qualify for SPD. Cornell will try and work it out with State. Court will do waiver of right to attorney verbally at the next hearing, must appear in person, continues bond, sets for AIA on 4/6/22 at 10:15 AM. Cornell makes statement in regards to appearing in person and this incident. Court - need to make arrangements to appear in person, call DA's Office and may be able to work the matter out. Cornell understands.
on petition for appointment of an attorney - denied

Adjourned initial appearance on March 16, 2022 at 09:45 am.

09:18 AM Defendant Tracy J Cornell appears by video.  Alexander Paul Seifert appeared for the State of Wisconsin appears by video. CC and CR appear by video. Cornell has received a copy of his complaint. Court reads charge and penatly. Cornell understands. Court questions if he has contacted an attorney. Cornell has contacted SPD is not eligible, contacted private hire and can not afford a private attorney. Court advises of options of obtaining an attorney - private hire or court appointed attorney. Cornell would like court appointed paperwork sent to him. Court will have set for AIA on 3/16/22 at 9:45 AM. State asks for $100 signature bond. Court will set bond at $100 with condition to sign and return to the COC office within 10 business days. Rebecca Lemman speaks regarding talking to DA's office. Court advises cannot give legal advise and explains if he wants to waive his right to an attorney. Clerk will send both, wiaver of right to attorney and court appointed attorney paperwork.
